üîç How It Works
XOR Encryption Principle
text
Plain Text:  H    e    l    l    o
ASCII:       72   101  108  108  111
Password:    s    e    c    r    e
ASCII:       115  101  99   114  101
XOR Result:  45   0    15   30   10
Password Padding
text
Text: "Hello" (5 chars)
Password: "ab" (2 chars)
Padded Password: "ababa" (repeats to match length)
üß™ Testing
Run the test suite:

bash
cargo test
Manual Testing
rust
// Quick test in main.rs
fn test_encryption_decryption() {
    let text = "Test Message";
    let password = "MyPass123";
    
    // Simulate encryption
    let padded = pad_or_trim(text.len(), password.as_bytes());
    let encrypted = zip_and_xor(&padded, text.as_bytes());
    
    // Simulate decryption
    let decrypted = decipher(&padded, encrypted);
    
    assert_eq!(decrypted, text);
}
üìä Performance
Encryption/Decryption: O(n) time complexity

Memory: Minimal allocations, uses iterators for lazy evaluation

No heap fragmentation: Pre-allocated vectors

üîí Security Notes
‚ö†Ô∏è Educational Use Only - This is NOT cryptographically secure:

XOR cipher alone is vulnerable to frequency analysis

No key derivation function (KDF)

No authentication or integrity checks

Password repeated in padding creates patterns

For real encryption, use:

AES-256-GCM

Argon2 for key derivation

Authenticated encryption modes
